    S &= \sum_{k=0}^{62} \binom{2014}{k}\\
    &= \sum_{k=0}^{62} \frac{2014!}{k!(2014-k)!} 
\end{align*} We can then subtract each binomial in the sum, one at a time, from $2017!$ this gives $$ - \binom{2014}{k} = \frac{2017!}{k!(2017-k)!}$$ We then have $$ S \equiv \sum_{k=0}^{62} \dbinom{2017}{k} \equiv \frac{2017!}{0!2017!}+\frac{2017!}{1!2016!}+...+\frac{2017!}{62!1955!} \bmod 2017$$ As $2017$ is prime, Wilson's theorem gives $$\equiv \frac{2017!}{0!2017!}+\frac{2017!}{1!2016!}+...+1 \bmod 2017$$ which will give the answer $\fbox{E}$.
